================================================================================
THIRD-PARTY COMPONENTS AND ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS
================================================================================

This project would not exist without the Game & Watch homebrew community. The
chainloader's own source under src/ is licensed under the BSD 3-Clause License
above, with two exceptions that remain the property of their authors and retain
their own headers:

  * src/chainloader/startup.s            — STMicroelectronics (CMSIS), (C) 2019
  * src/chainloader/system_stm32h7xx.c   — STMicroelectronics (CMSIS), (C) 2017

This project also builds upon, derives techniques and code from, and bundles the
following works, each of which remains under its own license. Where code is
derived from a BSD-3-Clause project, the notice below preserves that project's
copyright as required by clause 1 of its license.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Code and techniques derived into this project's source (BSD-3-Clause lineage)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* Original Game & Watch hardware hacking, bootloader, and the STM32 register
  sequences this work descends from
  — Konrad Beckmann (kbeckmann) and Thomas Roth (stacksmashing).

* game-and-watch-patch — OFW binary-patching and the append-and-redirect hook.
  src/patch/main.c is substantially derived from it (via Marian Muller's fork,
  which this project used as its reference) and contains portions copied verbatim
  (the LZMA decompression plumbing and patch entry scaffolding); the
  check_start_button() and chainloader() hook logic are original to this project.
  — Brian Pugh (https://github.com/brianpugh/game-and-watch-patch) and
    Marian Muller (https://github.com/marian-m12l/game-and-watch-patch),
    BSD-3-Clause.

* game-and-watch-patch (fork) — also the source of the bank-swapping technique
  that src/common/banks.h reimplements in bare-metal register form (no code
  copied verbatim; the option-byte sequence follows the STM32H7 reference manual).
  — Marian Muller (https://github.com/marian-m12l/game-and-watch-patch),
    BSD-3-Clause.

  The above BSD-3-Clause sources carry the notice:
    Copyright 2020 Konrad Beckmann, Thomas Roth, STMicroelectronics
  redistributed here under the same three conditions and disclaimer as stated
  in the BSD 3-Clause License above.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bundled third-party code (under deps/, each under its own license)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* STM32H7xx HAL Drivers and CMSIS device headers (deps/Drivers, deps/Core)
  — STMicroelectronics. HAL: BSD-3-Clause; CMSIS: Apache-2.0.

* LZMA decoder (deps/Core/Src/LzmaDec.c)
  — Igor Pavlov, LZMA SDK. Public domain.

* External flash memory mapper and JEDEC driver (deps/Core/Src/flash.c)
  — Derived from gnwmanager's Core/Src/flash.c (Copyright 2023 Brian Pugh, Apache-2.0)
    with SFDP reading logic ported from retro-go's gw_flash.c (Copyright 2021
    Sylver Bruneau and contributors, GPL-2.0).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Aggregated submodules (separate programs; not linked into the firmware binary)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* gnwmanager/ — host-side flashing/patching tool.
  — Brian Pugh (https://github.com/brianpugh/gnwmanager), Apache-2.0.

* retro-go-sd/ — Retro-Go launcher this chainloader hands control to at runtime.
  — Sylver Bruneau, Konrad Beckmann, and contributors
    (https://github.com/sylverb/game-and-watch-retro-go-sd), GPL-2.0.
  Distributed here as mere aggregation under GPLv2 §2; it retains the GPL-2.0
  license and is not combined with the BSD-licensed chainloader source.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Special thanks
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To the reverse engineers and developers who decoded the STM32H7 Game & Watch,
hacked it open, and built the community around it:
Thomas Roth (stacksmashing), Konrad Beckmann (kbeckmann), Brian Pugh
(BrianPugh), Sylver Bruneau (sylverb), and Marian Muller (marian-m12l).
